#### Issue details
I'm trying to rotate a Texture, fixate the camera to one point of it and also rotate the camera when the texture rotates.
That way I want my camera to stay on the exact same point and look like nothing is moving, although the object itself is indeed rotating.
When doing so I see pixel-stuttering on the rotated texture ( https://youtu.be/t72ZhC4Ejm4 ).

#### Reproduction steps/code
Rotate an object and use the projectionMatrix to fixate your camera to one point of it that you calculate relative to the rotation of the object. Then apply the same rotation to the camera that you apply to the texture. That way from the camera perspective everything should look like nothing is changing, since you cancle out all moving factors.
The problem is that you still see pixel-movement inside the texture.
**I attached a Demo-Project that reproduces this exact issue:**
[test.zip](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/files/768326/test.zip)

Here is the Code from the Game-Class 
```

package com.mygdx.game;

import com.badlogic.gdx.ApplicationAdapter;
import com.badlogic.gdx.Gdx;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.GL20;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.OrthographicCamera;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.Texture;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.SpriteBatch;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.TextureRegion;
import com.badlogic.gdx.math.MathUtils;
import com.badlogic.gdx.math.Vector2;
import com.badlogic.gdx.utils.viewport.ScreenViewport;
import com.badlogic.gdx.utils.viewport.Viewport;

public class MyGdxGame extends ApplicationAdapter {
    private static final int SIZE = 500;

    private Viewport viewport = new ScreenViewport();
    private SpriteBatch batch;
    private TextureRegion img;
    private float rotation = 0f;

    @Override
    public void create() {
        batch = new SpriteBatch();
        img = new TextureRegion(new Texture("badlogic.jpg"));
    }

    @Override
    public void render() {
        // Creating Viewport
        viewport.update(Gdx.graphics.getWidth(), Gdx.graphics.getHeight(), true);
        OrthographicCamera camera = (OrthographicCamera) viewport.getCamera();
        camera.viewportWidth = 1000;
        camera.viewportHeight = 1000;
        camera.zoom = 0.1F;

        final float camMod = Gdx.graphics.getDeltaTime() * 300F;
        rotation = translateRotation(rotation + camMod);

        final Vector2 pos = localToParentCoordinates(new Vector2(SIZE / 2, SIZE / 2));
        camera.position.set(pos, 0);
        camera.rotate(-camMod);
        camera.update();

        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(1, 0, 0, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
        batch.setProjectionMatrix(camera.combined);
        batch.begin();
        batch.draw(img, -SIZE / 2, -SIZE / 2, SIZE / 2, SIZE / 2, SIZE, SIZE, 1, 1, rotation);
        batch.end();
    }

    public Vector2 localToParentCoordinates(Vector2 localCords) {
        final float cos = MathUtils.cosDeg(360F - rotation);
        final float sin = MathUtils.sinDeg(360F - rotation);
        return new Vector2(
                localCords.x * cos + localCords.y * sin,
                localCords.x * -sin + localCords.y * cos
        );
    }

    public static float translateRotation(float degrees) {
        while (degrees > 360F) {
            degrees -= 360F;
        }
        while (degrees < 0F) {
            degrees += 360F;
        }
        return degrees;
    }
}

```

